Lokales Engagement als Gegenmittel gegen den Populismus
PARIS – Die einst die westlichen Demokratien dominierten Parteien wurden in ihrem Kern erschüttert.
Viele – u. a. in Frankreich, Italien, Griechenland und im Vereinigten Königreich – haben krachende Wahlniederlagen erlitten.
Andere haben sich so drastisch verändert, dass nur noch der Name geblieben ist.
Die Republikanische Partei von US-Präsident Donald Trump hat mit der des früheren Präsidenten Ronald Reagan kaum noch etwas gemein.
This development resembles what is happening everywhere in the West.
The leadership of the formerly dominant parties oscillate between denial and despair, while populists fish for their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and treat their supporters as "pitiable," as Hillary Clinton did just before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too frightened by the populist tide to launch a counter-offensive.
But neither denial nor self-satisfaction will dissolve the established political situation.
The progressives must reposition themselves, and this begins with diagnosing the shortcomings of the traditional parties.
Apart of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the true issues of our time.
Still caught on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored declining social mobility, intensifying environmental crises, increasing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other topics that actually matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were at the forefront.
Today, they stand alone in the forest, wondering where everyone else has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed off course.
The chasm between their objective analysis of reality and government policy has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have been aware for a long time of the increasing slope in income and other indicators between some prosperous, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
However, before the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national government leader had implemented tax cuts based on place of residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of French GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In the year 2016, Macron's movement En Marché! initiated the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the interviewers then became the basis for Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment well over a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of his opponents' jokes; however, their laughter quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, during which activists distribute flyers and cheer on the candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and retain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Trotz dieser Schwächen hatten die etablierten Parteien eine Anzahl von Vorteilen, die ihren Zusammenbruch hinauszögerten.
In den letzten Jahren hatten sie einen technologischen Vorsprung gegenüber weniger etablierten Gegnern, und sie waren die einzigen politischen Akteure mit organisierten Wählergruppen, die die Menschen zu den Wahlen mobilisieren, Proteste organisieren und Petitionen starten konnten.
Aber dieses Modell trägt nicht mehr.
Die Bürger weigern sich heutzutageweiher zu sein.
Zusammen mit einem höheren Bildungsniveau kamen neue Forderungen nach Teilhabe.
The voters want to be treated as political actors with their own rights and not as pawns in someone else's game.
In addition, governments themselves are no longer the sole providers of political measures.
This is one of the hard lessons we had to learn over the two years during which we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
The most pressing political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions provided solely by national governments.
These challenges require profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at both sub- and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered entry barriers for political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the party apparatus and solid support networks.
Anyone who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook does not need an old-fashioned party apparatus that has been around for centuries.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures rather than just elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed with people on the ground.
At La République En Marche!, we refer to this as local citizen projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to community vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering tailored solutions to local problems and thereby strengthening the communities.
Such projects should be considered today as indispensable supplements to public policy.
In the future, the ability of a party to offer rewarding ways for political and communal engagement will be crucial for its attractiveness.
And by demonstrating their reform policies daily "live," the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what needs to be said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win over the people.
Reconnecting with the concerns of voters thus goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need a progressive policy on the ground.
